<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<!--@import "_head.kit"-->

<body>
    <!--@import "_header.kit"-->

    <main>
        <article class="project-detail">
            <header class="project-detail-hero section-fade">
                <div class="container narrow">
                    <a href="/portfolio.html" class="back-link">Back to portfolio</a>
                    <p class="eyebrow">Project Two</p>
                    <h1>Eventbrite Wallet — Reducing Queues and Unlocking In-Event Revenue</h1>
                    <p class="lead">A product concept that expands Eventbrite beyond ticketing by introducing a digital
                        wallet for food, beverages and event services. The solution reduces purchase friction, improves
                        attendee experience and creates a new revenue opportunity for organizers and the platform.</p>
                </div>
            </header>

            <section class="project-media-section">
                <div class="container">
                    <div class="project-cover project-cover-two project-cover-wide"></div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section class="project-body-section">
                <div class="container detail-grid">
                    <div class="detail-content">
                        <h2>Overview</h2>
                        <p>Events are meant to be lived, not waited for. But in many live experiences, attendees lose
                            valuable time in queues while organizers lose revenue due to limited service capacity, poor
                            demand predictability and abandoned purchases.</p>

                        <p>The opportunity was to expand Eventbrite’s role beyond ticketing by supporting the full
                            event consumption journey. The proposed solution introduces a digital wallet inside the
                            Eventbrite app, allowing users to buy in advance or during the event and redeem purchases
                            with less friction.</p>
                        <h2>Process</h2>
                        <p>The design approach focused on two core journeys: pre-event purchase and in-event purchase.
                            Before the event, users can buy tickets and add drinks or services in advance. During the
                            event, they can purchase in real time, show a QR code and quickly return to the experience.
                        </p>

                        <p>The main design challenge was speed. In an event context, every extra step increases
                            friction. Instead of reinventing event consumption, the concept improves behaviors that
                            already exist: buying, paying and redeeming.</p>
                    </div>
                    <aside class="project-facts">
                        <h2>Details</h2>
                        <dl>
                            <dt>Date</dt>
                            <dd>January 2026</dd>
                            <dt>Team</dt>
                            <dd>3 members</dd>
                            <dt>Context</dt>
                            <dd>Academic</dd>
                            <dt>Role</dt>
                            <dd>Product Concept / UX Strategy / Business Opportunity / Flow Design</dd>
                            <dt>Methods:</dt>
                            <dd>Problem Framing, Journey Mapping, Product Strategy, Wireframing, Business Impact Estimation</dd>
                            <dt>Opportunity:</dt>
                            <dd>Reduced queue friction, higher attendee satisfaction, new in-event revenue stream</dd>
                        </dl>
                    </aside>
                </div>
            </section>
        </article>
    </main>

    <!--@import "_footer.kit"-->
</body>

</html>